<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="amino-acid-structure">Amino Acid: Structure</h2><h4 id="proteins">Proteins</h4><ul><li><p>Proteins are polymers (and macromolecules) made of monomers called <b>amino acids</b></p></li><li><p>The sequence, type and number of the amino acids within a protein determines its shape and therefore its function</p></li><li><p>Proteins are extremely important in cells because they form all of the following:</p><ul><li><p><b>Enzymes</b></p></li><li><p>Cell membrane proteins (eg. carrier)</p></li><li><p>Hormones</p></li><li><p>Immunoproteins (eg. immunoglobulins)</p></li><li><p>Transport proteins (eg. haemoglobin)</p></li><li><p>Structural proteins (eg. keratin, collagen)</p></li><li><p>Contractile proteins (eg. myosin)</p></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="amino-acids">Amino acids</h4><ul><li><p>Amino acids are the <b>monomers</b> of polypeptides</p></li><li><p>There are 20 amino acids found in proteins common to all living organisms</p></li><li><p>The general structure of all amino acids is a central carbon atom bonded to:</p><ul><li><p>An <b>amine</b> (also called amino) group -NH<sub>2</sub></p></li><li><p>A <b>carboxylic acid</b> group -COOH</p></li><li><p>A <b>hydrogen</b> atom</p></li><li><p>An <b>R</b> group (which is how each amino acid differs and why amino acid properties differ e.g. whether they are acidic or basic or whether they are polar or non-polar)</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Amino acid groups" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="793" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Amino-acid-groups.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/Amino-acid-groups.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The general structure of an amino acid</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="the-peptide-bond">The Peptide Bond</h2><ul><li><p>Peptide bonds form between amino acids</p></li><li><p>Peptide bonds are <b>covalent bonds</b> and so involve the sharing of electrons</p></li><li><p>In order to form a <b>peptide bond</b> :</p><ul><li><p>A hydroxyl (-OH) is lost from the carboxylic group of one amino acid</p></li><li><p>A hydrogen atom is lost from the amine group of another amino acid</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The remaining carbon atom (with the double-bonded oxygen) from the first amino acid bonds to the nitrogen atom of the second amino acid</p></li><li><p>This is a <b>condensation</b> reaction so water is released</p></li><li><p><b>Dipeptides</b> are formed by the condensation of <b>two</b> amino acids</p></li><li><p><b>Polypeptides</b> are formed by the condensation of <b>many</b> (3 or more) amino acids</p></li><li><p>A protein may have only one polypeptide chain or it may have multiple chains interacting with each other</p></li><li><p>During <b>hydrolysis</b> reactions, the addition of water <b>breaks the peptide bonds </b>resulting in polypeptides being broken down to amino acids</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Dipeptide formation" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="387" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Dipeptide-formation.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Dipeptide-formation.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Peptide bonds are formed by condensation reactions (releasing a molecule of water) and broken by hydrolysis reactions (adding a molecule of water)</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>When asked to identify the location of the peptide bond, look for where nitrogen is bonded to a carbon which has a double bond with an oxygen atom, note the R group is not involved in the formation of a peptide bond.</p><p>Structures of specific amino acids are not required.</p></div></div></div></div>